column25: We've had to ask the CDCAC warehouse to store our dry donations from the NW Harvest/Safeway Home Team Harvest holiday food drive, because we don't have adequate storage for dry goods (our local Safeway store sold over 1,400 $10 bags of food!).  We've also had to use freezer space of a local restaurant over the holidays because our freezers were maxed out with chickens, turkeys, hams, pies, etc.--holiday items.  In the summertime, when our gleaning program is harvesting fresh produce from area farms/gardens/orchards/etc. we've had to ask the CDCAC warehouse to store and help distribute this produce, due mainly to the abundance of food that is gleaned.
column38: We currently need more storage space and could really benefit from a walk-in cooler and freezer.  Certain times of the year, particularly during the holidays, we are maxed out with our space, especially our freezer space. Our food bank is currently housed in the same space as a thrift store, which is what helps us to stay open 6 days/week, but it also limits our food storage space.  That will soon change, however, as we will be separating the food bank and thrift store in the coming months.  Once that happens, we'll have much more space for food storage, and our food bank will become more of a shopping model.  That should help to alleviate our storage issues.  We're hoping part of that process could also include walk-ins.
A larger warehouse, so to better utilize our forklift.
